{"cursor":"10316","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nThe term 'watchdog journalism' is strongly related to the practice of\ninvestigative journalism. A watchdog is defined as \"a person or group of persons\nthat acts as a protector or guardian against inefficiency, illegal practices,\netc.\" by the [[Collins English Dictionary]]. Definition of \"watchdog\" in the\n[[Collins English Dictionary]], 2009. In news journalism, a watchdog\njournalist also fulfills this function of being a guardian. To perform in an\ninvestigative manner, the journalist is in the \"role\" of a watchdog. Nieman\nfoundation for Journalism at Harvard, 2012 Watchdog journalism cannot be\ndefined by the amount of investigation alone, however, but is used in many\ndifferent contexts. It also is stated \"contingent on the existing social,\npolitical, and economic conditions and a reflection as much of the historical\nmoment as it is of preâexisting structures and media cultures\". Coronel\n2008, p. 13 Watchdog journalism can be located in a variety of news media,\nsuch as radio, television, Internet, and print media where it may be seen as \"a\nunique strength of newspapers\", Ward 2005 and additional new media and\nconcepts such as weblogs and citizen journalism. Watchdog journalists also are\ncalled \"watchmen\", Hanitzsch 2007, p.373 \"agents of social control\",\nor \"moral guardians\". Berger 2000, 84\n\nAnother term in this context is the \"detached watchdog\". The concept of the\ndetached watchdog emerged from an extensive study on journalism cultures\nconducted by communication researcher Hanitzsch and others. The detached\nwatchdog is described as \"dedicated to objectivity, neutrality, fairness, and\nimpartiality\". Hanitzsch 2011, p.481\n","linknr":274,"url":"Watchdog_journalism","recorded":1374766346,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Watchdog_journalism&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Watchdog_journalism&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/open